<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Measurements.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">D = 15.4 mm, H = 8.1 mm (n = 1).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="differential diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Differential diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Differs from 
<taxonomicName genus="B." lsidName="B. procumbens" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="procumbens">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">B. procumbens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by having a more rounded shell shape and the last whorl is also more rounded. Most important are the extremely widely-spaced and prominent hair scars. This latter trait distinguishes 
<taxonomicName genus="B." lsidName="B. raripila" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="raripila">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">B. raripila</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. from all other similar species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="etymology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
The name 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pall-Gergely" authorityYear="2022" class="Gastropoda" family="Camaenidae" genus="Bouchetcamaena" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Bouchetcamaena raripila" order="Testacea" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="raripila">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Bouchetcamaena raripila</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
refers to the few hairs/hair scars on the shell surface (
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">rarus</emphasis>
: few, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">pilus</emphasis>
: hair in Latin).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
The new species is known from the type locality only. Kopanedza (also spelled Kopamedza) is situated in the Barail Range, Dafla Hills (India), although its exact locality is unknown (
